  "business_context": "User records are the CRM's authentication and authorization anchors: every record in the system has Created By, Last Modified By, and usually Owner / Assigned User references that point at User records. User records drive permissions (which records a person can see and edit), task and account assignment (\"Sarah owns this account\"), reporting filters (\"show me my open opportunities\"), and audit trails (\"who changed this field yesterday\"). Users typically have license tiers (Standard, Read-Only, Portal, etc.) that determine cost and capability. The User vs Contact distinction is sharp in most B2B systems but blurry in nonprofits: a staff member might also be a donor (so their record exists as both a User and a Contact); a board member might be a Contact who occasionally needs limited User access; a volunteer coordinator might be a User who is also tracked as a Contact for emergency contact purposes. When interviewing clients, surface \"User\" by asking who actually logs into the CRM (which is different from who appears in it) and what permission tiers they need: full access for staff, limited access for volunteers, read-only for executives, portal access for partners or board members. Bloomerang notably handles this differently — it doesn't expose User as an API entity at all because user management is administrative-only.",
